colors = ['#E6E6FA', '#800080']
for feature in features_with_na:
    data = dataset.copy()
    
    # 1 if NULL (Missing), 0 otherwise (Not Missing)
    data[feature] = np.where(data[feature].isnull(), 1, 0) 
    
    # 2. Group by 
    plot_data = data.groupby(feature)['SalePrice'].median()
    
    # 3. Plot the median SalePrice using the custom colors
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    plot_data.plot.bar(color=colors)
    
     
    plt.title(f'Median SalePrice by Missingness in {feature}', fontsize=12)
    plt.xlabel(f'{feature} Missing (1=Yes, 0=No)', fontsize=10)
    plt.ylabel('Median SalePrice', fontsize=10)
    plt.xticks(rotation=0) # Keep labels horizontal
    
    plt.show()

## We will be using logarithmic transformation
for feature in contineous:
    data = dataset.copy()
    
    # --- FIX: Coerce the column to numeric type ---
    # This converts the feature column to float, turning non-numeric values into NaN.
    data[feature] = pd.to_numeric(data[feature], errors='coerce') 
    
    # 1. Check for invalid data (NaN) created by coercion, or original zeros
    # Check if any value is zero or if all values became NaN (meaning the column was full of non-numeric strings)
    # The 'pass' condition is now slightly broader to skip problematic columns.
    if (0 in data[feature].unique()) or (data[feature].isnull().all()):
        print(f"Skipping '{feature}': Contains zeros or entirely non-numeric/NaN values.")
        pass
    else:
        # Perform Log Transformation
        data[feature] = np.log(data[feature])
        data['SalePrice'] = np.log(data['SalePrice'])
        
        # Plotting
        plt.scatter(data[feature], data['SalePrice'], s=10, alpha=0.6, color='#800080') # Added color/style
        plt.xlabel(feature, fontsize=12)
        plt.ylabel('Log SalePrice', fontsize=12)
        plt.title(f'{feature} (Log Transformed)', fontsize=14)
        plt.show()

for feature in contineous:
    data = dataset.copy()
    
    #  presence of zero values.
    if 0 in data[feature].unique():
        # Skip features with zero values as log(0) is undefined.
        print(f"Skipping '{feature}': Contains zero values, cannot log transform.")
        pass
    else:
        # Perform Log Transformation on the feature
        # (It's generally good practice to transform the target variable too, 
        # though only the feature is strictly necessary for this boxplot.)
        try:
            data[feature] = np.log(data[feature])
            # data['SalePrice'] = np.log(data['SalePrice']) # Optional, but recommended for full transformation
            
            # Create the boxplot for the transformed feature
            plt.figure(figsize=(4, 6))
            
            # Boxplot is called on the DataFrame 'data', specifying the column
            data.boxplot(column=feature) 
            
            # Customize the plot
            plt.ylabel(f'Log({feature})')
            plt.title(f'Distribution of Log({feature})')
            plt.xticks([1], ['']) # Remove the default X-axis tick label
            
            plt.show()

        except TypeError:
            # Catches the error if non-numeric data unexpectedly exists in a 'continuous' feature
            print(f"Skipping '{feature}': Encountered non-numeric data during log transformation.")
            pass
